%%TITLE
Prevalence of human papillomavirus in oral squamous cell carcinomas in northern Spain.
%%ABSTRACT
The aim of this study was to analyze the prevalence of high-risk HPV in oral squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC) in a northern Spanish population, as well as to ascertain the prognostic role of p16
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Patients and tissue specimens
A retrospective study was designed. Surgical tissue speci- mens from 125 patients with oral squamous cell carcinoma who underwent surgical treatment at the Hospital Univer- sitario Central de Asturias between 1996 and 2007 were retrospectively collected, in accordance to approved insti- tutional review board guidelines. Tissue specimens were obtained from the Biobanco del Principado de Asturias. All experimental protocols were approved by the Institutional Ethics Committee of the Hospital Universitario Central de Asturias and by the Regional CEIC from the Principado de Asturias. Informed consent was obtained from all patients. Representative tissue sections were obtained from archival, formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded blocks, and the histo- logical diagnosis was confirmed by an experienced pathologist (AA).
Tissue microarray (TMA) construction
Three morphological representative areas were selected from each individual tumor paraffin block. In addition,
each TMA contained morphologically normal oral mucosa samples from non-oncological patients undergoing oral surgery as internal negative controls, and also three cores of a HPV-positive cervix carcinoma as a positive control. To check the histopathological diagnosis and the adequacy of tissue sampling, a section from each microarray was stained with hematoxylin and eosin and examined by light microscopy.
Immunohistochemistry (IHC)
The TMAs were cut into 3-lm sections and dried on Flex IHC microscope slides (DakoCytomation, Glostrup, Den- mark). Immunohistochemistry was performed in all 125 samples using an automatic staining workstation (Dako Autostainer, Dako Cytomation, Glostrup, Denmark) using the Dako Envision Flex ? Visualization System (Dako Autostainer) and diaminobenzidine (DAB) chromogen as substrate. The following primary antibodies were used: anti-p53 clone DO-7 (Dako, Glostrup, Denmark), and anti- p16 clone E6H4 (Roche mtm laboratories AG, Heidelberg, Germany).
P16 and p53 immunostainings were evaluated by two independent observers (JPR and JMGP). P16 immunos- taining was scored as positive when the number of diffuse nuclear and cytoplasmic stained cells was higher than 70 %. P53 immunostaining was evaluated as positive when more than 10 % of the malignant cells showed nuclear staining.
HPV DNA detection by in situ hybridization (ISH)
ISH was performed with biotinylated HPV DNA probes considered to react with HPV types 16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 39,
45, 51, 52, 56, 58, 59, and 68 (Y1443, DakoCytomation, Glostrup, Denmark) on all 125 oral SCC using 3-lm for- malin-fixed, paraffin-embedded tissue sections of the TMAs, according to the manufacturer’s instructions. Focal positive staining in the nuclei of tumor cells indicated the presence of HPV.
Tumor HPV DNA detection by PCR
PCR was performed in all cases, where p16INK4a expres- sion was positive. HPV genomic sequences were detected by polymerase chain reaction (PCR) amplification using degenerate consensus primers MY11/GP6? [, ] complementary to the conserved L1 region (these primers are known to detect the vast majority of HPV types com- monly associated with cervical cancer) []. Amplification of a b-globin gene fragment was performed to control for target DNA integrity. The products were analyzed by electrophoresis on 2 % agarose gel, stained with ethidium
bromide. In addition, detection of HPV infection was determined using the automated Cobas 4800 system (Roche, USA). This test detects and amplifies a broad spectrum of HR-HPV genotypes as well as co-amplifying the human cellular b-globin gene. Each deparaffinized sample was added to 20 ml of STE medium in a container specific to the equipment and positive control samples, and negative control samples were processed in each run. Following detection, eluted-purified DNA was used for PCR HPV detection. In this study, detection and PCR amplification was carried out in a single tube, where probes with 4 different reporter dyes tracked different targets in the multiplex reaction: dye 1 tracked HPV 31, 33, 35, 39,
45, 51, 52, 56, 58, 59, 66, and 68, dyes 2 and 3 tracked HPV 16 and 18, respectively, while dye 4 targeted b- globin.
Statistical analyses
Categorical data were compared using v2 or Fisher’s exact (when cell frequencies were less than 5) tests. The overall survival was defined as the period from the patient’s first visit to our department until the end of the study. Cause- specific survival time was calculated from the time of diagnosis until the time of death. The Kaplan–Meier method was used to estimate the survival curves, and the comparison between survival functions for different strata was assessed with the log-rank tests. Multivariate Cox proportional hazards models were used to examine the relative impact of any variable found to be statistically significant in the univariate analysis, and a significance level of 0.10 was used to determine the independent fac- tors. All tests were two sided with p values B0.05 as the threshold to be considered statistically significant. All statistical analyses were performed using the computer package PASW Statistics 18 (SPSS Inc., Chicago, IL, USA).
